comments.body: Yes @wolfgang_wuster this is a very challenging group. To make things even more complicated (or interesting), the B. sonene mt DNA clade includes specimens and samples from Peru to Brazil, in the Serra de Ricardo Franco/ Serrania de Huanchaca/ Serra da Borda region. All  records from this entire region,  in B mattogrossensis, in the northwesternmost expanses of savannas (Beni, Chiquitania and Cerrado) in Bolivia, Peru and the Brazil/Bolivia border, could well be B. sonene.  And B sonene will have to be added to the list of Brazilian snakes. I think it makes sense, and nice to see things slowly moving forward.

results.place_guess: Parque Nacional Mapinguari, Canutama, AM, BR

identifications.body: Part of the B. neuwiedi complex, but certainly not B. neuwiedi sensu stricto. In terms of mtDNA phylogeny, the populations from northern Bolivia are closest to Bothrops sonene according to Carrasco et al. 2019, but whether they are the same or not is unclear. The entire B. neuwiedi group needs a lot of further work. Bothrops sp. is as good as it gets for the time being.
